  1. Are variations in air temperature, SST, and SSS associated with changes in cover?
    #All unique combinations for environmental variables
##Get all unique combinations of SST, air temp, SSS, and SST:SSS at 1 month lag. 
#First create the list of variables
lag1.vars <- c("SEFI_SST_mean.1",  "air_temp_mean.1", "SEFI_SSS_mean.1", "SEFI_SST_mean.1:SEFI_SSS_mean.1")
##Now get all unique combinations
#all values (4)
combn(unique(lag1.vars), 4)
##      [,1]                             
## [1,] "SEFI_SST_mean.1"                
## [2,] "air_temp_mean.1"                
## [3,] "SEFI_SSS_mean.1"                
## [4,] "SEFI_SST_mean.1:SEFI_SSS_mean.1"
#3 values per list
combn(unique(lag1.vars), 3)
##      [,1]              [,2]                             
## [1,] "SEFI_SST_mean.1" "SEFI_SST_mean.1"                
## [2,] "air_temp_mean.1" "air_temp_mean.1"

## [2,] "SEFI_SSS_mean.1"                 "SEFI_SSS_mean.1"                
## [3,] "SEFI_SST_mean.1:SEFI_SSS_mean.1" "SEFI_SST_mean.1:SEFI_SSS_mean.1"
#2 values per list

#AIC - Q1, all upright, one month lag This is to answer my first question about heat stress

Save AIC results as a CSV

write.csv(umodel1_aic, "C:/Users/Elizabeth Max/iCloudDrive/Thesis/Data/R/umodel1_aic.csv", row.names = TRUE)

Make a nice table of Upright model AIC rank results

#Use sjplot to create HTML table
umodel1_table <-
  tab_df(umodel1_aic,  #models to table
         alternate.rows = TRUE,
         title = "AIC Model Ranking Results - all upright species. SEFI environmental variables lagged 1 month.",
          col.header = c( #Default headers are okay, these are better
            "Model",
            "K",
            "AIC",
            "Delta AIC",
            "AIC Wt",
            "Cum. Wt",
            "LL"
            ),
         CSS = list( #Use CSS to modify table appearance
           css.footnote = 'text-align: left; '
         ),
         footnote = "<i>K</i> = multiplier penalty term depending on the number of terms in the model.<br/>
          <i>AIC</i> = Aikaki Information Criterion (AIC); models with lower AIC values contain more information.<br/>
         <i>Delta AIC</i> = Change in AIC value from top ranked model.<br/>
         <i>AIC Wt</i> = weight of evidence for given model.</br>
         <i>Cum.Wt</i> = cumulative AIC weight.</br>
         <i>LL</i> = log-likelihood of given model.",
         show.footnote = TRUE)

print(umodel1_table)

#Plot one of the top ranked regression models plugged into AIC

# Load the necessary library for plotting
library(ggplot2)

# Create a scatter plot of SEFI_SSS_mean.1 vs upalgae with the regression line
sampleregression <- ggplot(masterfile, aes(x = SEFI_SSS_mean.1, y = upalgae)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue", alpha = 0.6) +  # Scatter plot of raw data
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +  # Add the fitted regression line
  labs(x = "Sea Surface Salinity", y = "Algal Cover", 
       title = "Effect of Sea Surface Salinity on Algal Cover (Linear Regression)") +
  theme_minimal() +
  annotate("text", x = 34.5, y = 50, label = paste(round(summary(ua1.3.1)$r.squared, 3)), size = 5, color = "red")  # Annotate R-squared value

#with shaded confidence interval

# Load necessary library
library(ggplot2)

# Scatter plot with regression line and shaded confidence interval
simpreg <- ggplot(masterfile, aes(x = SEFI_SSS_mean.1, y = upalgae)) +
  geom_point(color = "lightblue", alpha = 0.6) +  # Scatter plot with light blue points
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE, color = "blue") +  # Linear regression line with shaded confidence interval
  labs(x = "Sea Surface Salinity", y = "Algal Cover", 
       title = "Effect of Sea Surface Salinity on Algal Cover (Linear Regression)") +
  theme_minimal()
plot(simpreg)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
